40|$|We use {{the quantum}} {{kinematic}} approach to revisit geometric phases associated with polarizing processes of a monochromatic <b>light</b> <b>wave.</b> We give the expressions of geometric phases for any, unitary or non-unitary, cyclic or non-cyclic transformations of the <b>light</b> <b>wave</b> state. Contrarily to the usually considered case of absorbing polarizers, {{we found that}} a <b>light</b> <b>wave</b> passing through a polarizer may acquire in general a non zero geometric phase. This geometric phase exists {{despite the fact that}} initial and final polarization states are in phase according to the Pancharatnam criterion and can not be measured using interferometric superposition. Consequently, {{there is a difference between}} the Pancharatnam phase and the complete geometric phase acquired by a <b>light</b> <b>wave</b> passing through a polarizer. We illustrate our work with the particular example of total reflection based polarizers. Comment: 17 pages, 4 figures, accepted for publication in Physica...|$|R
